node.text:
“Dear Penny,

My mother-in-law is 89 and in good health. The reason I’m writing is that in August 2019, my father-in-law died … When my father-in-law was in the hospital, my husband spoke to his sister about financial needs. My sister-in-law and her husband have helped my in-laws for years but said they were tapped out. [My husband] gave them a check for $5,000, money taken out on one of our credit cards. 

My sister-in-law accepted the check but completely shut my husband out of participating in my father-in-law's funeral mass. Even after my husband asked if he could say the eulogy, she informed him she was saying the eulogy and had already selected other family members for other participating parts. 

She had five pages to speak from, but she only mentioned herself, her husband and their dog on how meaningful our father-in-law was in their lives. She said nothing about her seven siblings, or the 13 grandchildren and 11 great-grandchildren … 

I’m expecting the same outcome for my mother-in-law's funeral, except this time I’m going to tell my husband that we will not help with any funeral expenses. If he insists, I only want him to give $500 not $5,000 … I realize my resentment is obvious in my letter, but I do want us to do the right thing. What should we do?”

Read Dear Penny’s response at the link in our bio 👀

So just how hard is it to get an 800 credit score? 

We wanted to find out, so we checked in with people who have already earned that elite status to find out exactly what they’ve done to get there. 

If you’re hoping to join the 800+ club, copy these nine habits that people with nearly perfect credit scores have in common.

It’s not just you. 

The cost of things like rent, electricity and even food are rising, and we’re pretty much all starting to feel the pinch.

More than a third of American households are inhabited by renters — which means more than a third of American households have landlords.

But the relationship between renter and landlord can be fraught, and it can be frustrating to be told to “deal with it” when you’re shelling out a third or your income (or more!) to live somewhere. 

The good news? As a renter, you have rights. Those rights may vary by state local jurisdiction, but the most basic right is to a residence that is in good enough condition to be lived in (also known as a warranty of habitability). 

Beyond that, responsibility for repairs and other issues that arise is dictated by what’s outlined in your lease agreement. That’s why it’s vital to read the entire lease and make sure you understand everything in it before you sign it. (And if you don’t understand something, ask!)

Head to the link in our bio for a ton of info on renters rights — and how to protect yourself. Plus, read up on your obligations as a renter (because yes, landlords have rights, too).
